text: I read the book as a kid and can already see they missed the entire point.  It wasn't a "horror creature feature".  The protagonist was a scientist who actually wanted to preserve the shark, and the plot followed the actual shark itself as it struggled to survive out of time (and eventually found a mate in the sequel).  Anytime the shark did something horrific, it was usually because some guy screwed something up.  Also, the premise was that the protagonist was exploring the Mariana Trench with a colleague and accidentally lured the shark to the surface...not chillin' with his family in this undersea condo made of glass.

text: Its been decades speculating that Megalodon still lives but I find it bull. Sure the ocean is big and have more mystery on it but I don't believe a million years old big-ass shark managed to survived till now. A lot of changes happen during all those times like the circulation of the ocean temperature and currents that affect living organisms. Quite sometimes that something weird is brought upon by witness that fares in the big blue.  I do in fact have a hypothesis that a prehistoric shark may survived with a unique adaptation to the environment like mostly in cold deeper waters. Not big though like an 18 meters (59 ft) fish but somehow in medium-bigger size than today Great White Shark. If this kind of shark do managed to survived, I would think its mostly around the South Pacific where its the best place remain secluded and unknown to others to find out.

Steve Alten's books have been waiting for their chance to go to the big screen for a loooong time and I feel like this movie was a squandered chance to make that happen. text: This movie really missed an opportunity. You see the difference between Rainn Wilson and Jeff Bloom is that Jeff Bloom takes himself serious, and you believe it. The original Jurassic Park hit a home run with the believability of the T-Rex scenes. You actually thought this was happening in the big theaters; it was a movie making marvel. Somethings is missing with these new blockbusters. There is a lack or seriousness, with sardonic actors that pretend they are the next Joss Whedon fanboy favorite. If you go Joss Whedon, you do it all the way. A movie like this, however, deserved to be taken serious. It could have created a new type of Jurassic Park phenomenon, not to mention that there is a dedicated number of people who believe that the Megalodon still exists in the deep seas.

text: not interested in this film.  That trailer showed way too much of the shark.  That part in the beginning? Thats that for me. If I ended up going to see this film (which I'm not) I wouldn't feel an ounce of suspense. Jaws set the standard on how to make a suspenseful shark flick.  The official theatrical trailer is also a big tease if you look at it in context (pretend you never heard of or seen the film). you dont see one inch of that shark's face, nor do you see it visibly attacking anyone. You're left to wonder what it looks like and what else it does - you essentially have to go to the cinema to find out yourself.  The Meg, on the other hand, was already shown to me.  I know what the shark looks like, I know who the characters are and I know the shark gets killed at the end on a particular scene, because this is what movie trailers do and I have absolutely no idea why I even try to give them the benefit of the doubt every time.  i am avoiding this

text: My honest review of the Meg, I went and saw it and paid almost $20 for my ticket:  Movie overall was a 3/10 whereas Altens books are 1/10 and maybe at best a 2/10. You can tell the movie was filmed in a giant pool for most scenes. The CGI was not the best , but it was the best it could be for a B movie shark flick, however this was not a cheap B movie it was an expensive $150 million dollar flop. Deep blue sea is by far better as is the original Jaws. If they used animatronics for this movie you would probably be looking at a $500 million dollar budget. The story line was stupid but it has some very nice scenes and funny punch lines. Megalodon was 70-90 feet? Megalodon feared nothing? Hahaha Only 2 references made to the Killer whales, the creatures responsible in part for megalodon extinction. It went to the primordial sea but couldn't find tropical waters?¬† Save your money and wait until it comes to Netflix or some other streaming service. I wasted almost 2 hours and almost$20 dollars, hopefully other people don't have to.

A slim hook, some falling over from the boat into water, a lucky escape or misfortune here and there, you know the usual scenes... cuz, Science B**ch! üåö  Second Half: Alright, enough with the science, we take the direction towards "Jaws" now. Voila, now this completed our mainstream "shark movie" touch.  But wait, what about adding helicopters? text: I'm an 11 year old female and I've always dreamed of becoming an *Elasmonbranchologist* |A marine biologist that mainly focuses on sharks|, I've been studying the megalodon for a few months and it would be great if some of you would give some feedback on how I'm doing!    1. A fully grown adult megalodon could grow up to 60 ft in height and the newly born babies were 40 ft in height.  2.The megalodon went extinct 2.6 million years ago due to the lack of prey.   |Now some people have asked me,*who would win, the T-Rex or the megalodon*|  -well that's hard to say because the T-Rex was on land while the megalodon was in water, but...the megalodon had a much bigger jaw and was much bigger than the T-Rex so In my opinion the megalodon would win.    |Now for some shark facts|  -The 5 most known sharks to be aggressive are-  The Oceanic White Tip The Great White The Shortfin Mako The Bull Shark The Tiger Shark  |How to defend yourself Incase of a not so pleasant shark encounter|  -Punch the shark in the eye |cant do that with a great white because it rolls its eyes in the back of its socket for protection|  -Punch it in the snout-  -Punch it in the gills-      |Guys I know I wrote a lot but I just want to say something...sharks kill 6-10 people a year but you wanna know how much sharks get killed by us...100 Million...each year....its because people have a horrible view on them...we need sharks for our eco system and they do a huge role in the food chain...so please dont think that these beautiful creatures of the sea are horrible monsters....Thanks for reading if you got up to here and please I would love feedback

text: *AVOID THIS MOVIE*  What an absolute cluster fuck of a movie. Where do I even begin with this one. A couple minutes into the movie I was cringing so hard in my seat and knew it was going to be the same throughout. But I relunctanty carried on.   The characters and their acting were awful and showed little to no emotion throughout the film, sometimes not even mourning the death of their friends for more than a few minutes or not even panicking when in the water or on the boat when there is a huge megaladon lurking in the water?   There was little to no suspense in the film and each scene was extremely predictable.   Also the IQ of the characters were extremely questionable throughout and quite laughable. Like multiple people falling off boats by standing at the back edge of them and dumb helicopter pilots, who can‚Äôt keep their eyes open and end up crashing into each other? And someone bright idea to send a couple of tiny little submarines the size of a car to take out a huge shark that is the length of a ship? And what happened to the chinese destroyers that we‚Äôre meant to be on their way? Could have been a lot safer and logical?   And talking about characters, do all blockbuster films these days need to have a character of every single different ethnicity they can think of. Do they purposely do this just to tick all the boxes so everyone is pleased in the mainstream? It‚Äôs super unrealistic and super cringe.   I have probably missed some other dumb things but this movie was quite frankly terrible, boring, predictable and extremely cliche. Please don‚Äôt waste your time watching this movie unless you are into what myself and many others have described it to be.

text: More facts about it in the U.S. about 1 or 3 people die a YEAR from shark attacks and humans kill 100 MILLION sharks a year. We get 19 shark attacks a year (again only 1-3 usually die) so that means that you are more likely to get struck by lightning (it kills 37 people each year) then get attacked by a shark. Sharks need to continue to move to be able to breathe in the water so if you are skinny (not like a stick you can be cubby just no fat) the shark may attack you but if you put up a fight it will not waste its time on something that will provide low calories. A shark has eyes on the side of its head so if you are below it or above it, it is a very low chance it will even see you. Just some fun facts about sharks that will help you not be so scared of them anymore (if you even are scared of sharks)
